subSubSection.paragraph:
Coquillett (1893a) described
Thereva novella
based on five males and one female from Los Angeles County, California , which had the “style of antennae two-fifths as long as the third joint; pile and bristles of vertex and bristles of occiput yellowish-white; thorax destitute of black pile; knob of halteres brown, margined with yellow; veins of wings largely yellow, stigma also yellow and indistinct”. The thorax lacking black setae and the yellow veins of the wings which lack any brown markings would key this species out to
Acrosathe vialis
or
A. falcata .
Several specimens with the label “Los Angeles County, California , Collection Coquillett” (MEI 113537, 113562–3, 113572–3) have been identified as
A. vialis .
No specimens of
A. falcata
have been identified from southern California ( Fig. 51 ). Also, several males and females of
A. vialis
have been found to have pale postocular and occipital macrosetae. Although the syntypes of
Thereva novella
could not be located in the USNM, I am synonomizing
Thereva novella
with
Acrosathe vialis
based on the wing veins being yellow and lacking brown margins and the type locality for the syntypes of
Thereva novella
being Los Angeles County, California .

Diagnosis. The male of
Acrosathe vialis
is similar to
A. falcata
in having the eyes holoptic, the ommatidia smaller ventrally and laterally, the wing veins and cross-veins lacking a dark brown margin, and having the setae on the head and thorax white to dark yellow. It differs from
A. falcata
in having the male sternite 8 (Fig. 44) with setae continuous across posterior margin; the aedeagus with AAP (Figs. 48) curved dorsally, extending two-thirds length of distiphallus, with apex recurved (Fig. 46); and the gonostylus dorsal view (as in Fig. 21 ) lacking a lateral, pointed flange. The female of
Acrosathe vialis
is similar to
A. bimaculata
and
A. otiosa
in having the frons with a dark brown pubescent area (as in Fig. 7 ).
Acrosathe vialis
and
A. bimaculata
are separated from
A. otiosa
in lacking a brown margin on the wing veins and cross-veins. It is separated from
A. bimaculata
in having the scape subequal to the width of the flagellum and the furca (Fig. 49) narrow, elongate, over twice as long as wide.

Head. Length 0.92–1.42, 1.09 mm . Ocellar tubercle dark reddish brown, pubescence gray; setae black, elongate. Eyes holoptic, separated by distance 0.1 times width of median ocellus; ommatidia smaller ventrally and laterally. Frons pubescence gray, dense, dark brown along dorsal margin; setae primarily white (occasionally intermixed with dark brown setae; occasionally completely dark brown). Antenna dark brown, pubescence gray, dense on scape and pedicel; antenna/head length 0.77–1.20, 0.82; scape length 0.24–0.40, 0.35 mm , width 0.14–0.18, 0.16 mm , length/width 1.7–2.5, 2.2, scape/pedicel length 2.4–4.2, 3.1, scape/ flagellum width 1.0–1.1, 1.1, setae white, elongate, macrosetae dark reddish brown; pedicel length 0.10–0.12, 0.11 mm , width 0.14–0.18, 0.15 mm , length/width 0.63–0.86, 0.74, setae white (occasionally intermixed with dark brown setae); flagellum length 0.35–0.42, 0.43 mm , width 0.14–0.18, 0.15 mm , length/width 2.6–3.4, 2.9, flagellum/scape length 0.9–1.5, 1.2. Parafacial pubescence gray; setae white, elongate on lateral half (occasionally with dark brown setae dorsolaterally). Maxillary palpus brown, pubescence white, dense; length 0.28–0.66, 0.48 mm , width 0.06–0.12, 0.08 mm , length/width 3.5–9.7, 6.3; setae white, elongate. Genal setae white, elongate. Occipital setae white, elongate; macrosetae dark brown (occasionally pale to dark yellow). Postocular macrosetae dark brown (occasionally pale to dark yellow).

Thorax. Macrosetae dark reddish brown 2–3, 3 np, 1–2, 2 sa, 1 pa, 0–2, 1 dc. Mesonotum dark brown, pubescence gray, dense, vittae absent; setae white, elongate, erect. Postpronotal setae white, elongate. Prosternum setae white. Pleuron pubescence gray, dense; setae white, elongate on propleuron, anepisternum, katepisternum, laterotergite, metanepisternum, and scutellum. Wing. Membrane hyaline, veins brown (occasionally with brown margin at apical margin of bm ); length 4.8–6.7, 6.0 mm, width 1.5–2.3, 2.0 mm, length/width 2.5–3.2, 2.9; cell m 3 closed, petiolate. Halter stalk dark brown, knob dark yellow. Legs. Coxae dark brown, pubescence whitish gray, dense; setae white, elongate; apical macrosetae dark reddish brown, hindcoxa with 1 posterolateral macroseta. Femora dark brown, pubescence whitish gray, dense; ventral setae white, elongate, dorsal setae white, appressed. Tibiae dark yellow becoming dark reddish brown apically. Tarsus 1 dark yellow, apex dark reddish brown; 2–5 dark reddish brown.

Abdomen. Pubescence white, dense; dorsal setae white, elongate, appressed; lateral setae white, erect.
Terminalia
(MEI 072392) dark reddish brown. Tergite 8 (Fig. 43), setae white. Sternite 8 (Fig. 44) rectangular, sides tapered posteriorly; posterior margin slightly emarginate medially; setae white, continuous across posterior margin. Epandrium (Fig. 43), dark brown, longer medially than wide; anterior margin broadly emarginate with sclerotized collar; posterolateral margin pointed; setae white. Cerci (Fig. 43) ending distal to apex of hypoproct. Hypoproct (Fig. 43), posterior margin truncate, ending basal to apex of cerci. Gonocoxite ventral view (Fig. 44), median margin straight then tapering towards narrow, clavate posterolateral projection, setae white, macrosetae dark brown; lateral view (Fig. 45) oval, tapered posteriorly to thick point. Gonostylus (as in Fig. 21 ). Aedeagus with dorsal apodeme (Fig. 46) narrow, sides emarginate, anterior margin rounded; ventral apodeme (Fig. 47) narrow, reaching anterior margin of dorsal apodeme; distiphallus dorsal view (Fig. 46) tapered posteriorly, slightly bulbous apically, lateral view (Fig. 48) sinuous, AAP ( Figs. 6 , 48) sinuate, apex curved dorsally, extending three-fourths length of distiphallus; ejaculatory apodeme (Fig. 46) reaching anterior margin of dorsal apodeme.

subSubSection.paragraph: FEMALE. Similar to male except for following. Variation (n=10).

Head. Length 1.00–1.28, 1.14 mm . Frons pubescence whitish gray, dense on ventral third, brownish gray on dorsal third with large, dark brown, pubescent circle dorsolaterally (as in Fig. 7 ), pale yellowish brown pubescence between and ventral to dark brown pubescent circles; setae pale yellow, elongate on ventral fourth with dark brown setae ventral to ocellar tubercle. Antenna/head length 0.79–0.95, 0.85; scape length 0.34–0.44, 0.38 mm , width 0.14–0.18, 0.17 mm , length/width 2.1–2.8, 2.3, scape/pedicel length 3.1–4.0, 3.4, scape/flagellum width 1.0–1.1, 1.0, setae pale yellow, elongate; pedicel length 0.10–0.12, 0.11 mm , width 0.14–0.16, 0.16 mm , length/width 0.6–0.8, 0.7; flagellum length 0.44–0.52, 0.47 mm , width 0.14–0.16, 0.16 mm , length/width 2.6–3.7, 2.9, flagellum/scape length 1.2–1.5, 1.2. Maxillary palpus pale brown; length 0.44–0.64, 0.60 mm , width 0.06–0.12, 0.10 mm , length/width 5.3–8.0, 6.5; setae pale yellow, elongate. Genal setae whitish yellow, elongate. Occipital setae pale yellow, elongate; macrosetae dark brown.

Thorax. Macrosetae 2–3, 3 np, 2 sa, 1 pa, 0–2, 0 dc. Mesonotum pubescence brownish gray; setae whitish yellow on prosternum, propleuron, anepisternum, katepisternum, laterotergite, metanepisternum, and scutellum. Wing. Length 6.7–7.5, 6.8 mm , width 1.8–2.5, 2.1 mm , length/width 2.7–3.4, 3.2; cell m 3 closed at wing margin or open slightly.

Abdomen. Dark brown, pubescence white to whitish gray, dense; dorsal setae white to whitish elongate on tergite 1 becoming short appressed posteriorly; lateral setae white to whitish yellow.
Terminalia
(MEI 011602) dark reddish brown, glossy. Furca (Fig. 49) oblong, greater than twice as long as wide, anterior margin rounded; length 0.86 mm , width 0.26 mm ; anterolateral projection short.
Immature stages. One male (MEI 012499) has been reared from a larva sieved at Zmudowski State Beach, California .

Distribution.
Acrosathe vialis
is known from Arizona , California , Idaho , Nevada , Oregon , Utah , Washington , and Wyoming ( Fig. 54 ).

Habitats and Phenology.
Acrosathe vialis
has primarily been hand-netted or collected in antifreeze pit traps; in Malaise traps in riparian meadows, damp creek beds, and sand areas; or hand-netted on
Salix gooddingii C.R. Ball
and
Salix lasiolepis Benth.
Adults have been collected from March through November.

Specimens examined. Type specimens.
Six syntype males (MEI 134314–9) of
Thereva vialis
were examined from the MCZ (Type No. 10677) with the following label information: First label red with handwritten number "10677" and white border with typeset "Type"; second label white with handwritten "Yosemite, Cal., June 5, O. S." [MEI 134316], "June 9, O. Sacken " [MEI 134418], "June 11, O. S." [MEI 134415, 134419), and "June 14, O. S." [MEI 134414, 134417]; third label white with typeset " O. Sacken " and "West. Dipt." handwritten in ink. The male (MEI 134316) is designated as the lectotype ( MCZ )
. This lectotype is designated in order to fix the concept of
Thereva vialis Osten Sacken
and to ensure universal and consistent interpretation of the same. The other males labeled MEI 134314–5, 134317–9 are designated as paralectotypes (MCZ).
Coquillett based his description of
Thereva novella
on five males and one female syntypes from Los Angeles County , California . None of these syntypes could be found in USNM collection.
